	<H1 CLASS="start2">
Greek and Roman Authors on LacusCurtius
	</H1>


<TABLE CLASS="basicH leadoff checkColor">
	<TR><TD><IMG TITLE="" CLASS="basicH" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/master.jpg
			" ALT="
[image ALT: A page of a parchment manuscript with rather hard to read pasty letters.]
	"></TD></TR>
	<TR><TD CLASS="paleo"><DIV CLASS="contents">
		<P CLASS="a0 center">
		<B>
Part of the opening lines of Frontinus's book
		<BR>
on the water supply of Rome
		</B>
		<BR>
(13th- or 14th-century&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref:date_of_Frontinus_manuscript" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/home.html#note:date_of_Frontinus_manuscript
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,MyNote,WIDTH,150)"
onMouseOut="nd();">a</A>
manuscript: Codex Cassinensis 361)
		<P CLASS="b0 justify small">
— but don't believe everything you see: the color is by yours truly.
		<A HREF="
Images/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/ms*/1/1.jpg
		"TARGET="pannellino"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Photo,WIDTH,110)"
onMouseOut="nd();"
onClick="makeWindow(1100,300)">
Here
		</A>
is the black &amp; white photo from 1899.
	</DIV></TD></TR>
</TABLE>


	<P CLASS="start2 justify">
A good number of these classical texts by ancient authors, whether in the original language or in translation, are not to be found elsewhere online. They all have one further point in common: each one has a full set of local links, down to the section level, according to a consistent scheme in each case — see the respective sourcecode — so you can target your link to the exact passage needed.


	<H3>
Latin Texts
	</H3>

<DIV ALIGN="center">
<TABLE CLASS="rubric">
	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Pliny_the_Elder/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric4" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Pliny_the_Elder/icon.jpg
			" ALT="
[image ALT: engraving of an erupting volcano]
			"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
			<B>
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Pliny_the_Elder/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
The Natural History of Pliny the Elder:
			</A>
			</B>
the complete Latin text as established by Karl Mayhoff in 1897‑1908. Here and there, annotated, illustrated with photos of my own, and linked to the Gazetteer, the Atlas, and the best and most stable sites on the Web.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete Latin text
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric2" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/icon.jpg
			" ALT="
[image ALT: A diagram of a basin receiving water from an ascending pipe.]
			"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="a0 start justify">
			<B>
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/De_Aquis/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Frontinus on the Water Supply of Rome:
			</A>
			</B>
In the early 2c <SPAN CLASS="small">A.D.</SPAN> Sextus Julius Frontinus was called on to administer the city's water, and methodically set out to discover and put an end to endemic theft of the resource, and prevent it in the future. Having done so, he wrote a very accurate and engagingly sober book about it, which is a mine of information for modern archaeologists and historians. Of everything Roman I've ever read, this is my favorite work, and I'm pleased to be able to share it with you.
			<P CLASS="i1 b0 justify">
In progress, if at a glacial pace: I'm linking each paragraph of the Latin to a photograph of it in the only surviving ancient <B>manuscript</B>, sometimes commented with a rudimentary apparatus: so far, 13 of these 130 paragraphs of the facsimile are online.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete Latin text and English translation
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Vitruvius/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric2" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Vitruvius/icon.jpg
			" ALT="
[image ALT: A ten-columned temple surmounted by a pyramid capped with a quadriga. It is a 19th‑century idea of the Mausoleum of Halicarnassus.]
			"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
			<B>
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Vitruvius/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Vitruvius on Architecture:
			</A>
			</B>
another work I expected would have been online long before this. Since it has failed to appear courtesy of anyone else, I entered it myself.
			<!-- DATEDTEXT --><B>[</B>The next step would ideally be to add commentary and many, many drawings.<B>]</B>
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete Latin text and English translation
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Sallust/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric2" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Sallust/icon.jpg
			" ALT="
[image ALT: A photograph of the sculptured bust of a stern-faced old man. It is a modern imaginative portrait of the ancient Roman historian Sallust. On this site, it serves as the icon for the works of Sallust.]">
			</A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="a0 start justify">
			<B>
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Sallust/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Sallust's <I>Catiline</I> and <I>Jugurthine War</I>
			</A>
			</B>
are among the best-written works onsite. The story of Catiline's revolt is interesting to students of Roman history as a dry run for Caesar's revolution; but also to modern man, dealing as it does with terrorism, the infiltration of republican government, and preëmptive strikes at them to preserve liberty. Similarly, the war with Jugurtha deals among other things with conducting a foreign war with a polarized citizenry, in which the defeatist half may have been bribed by the enemy to call off the war.
			<P CLASS="i1 b0  justify">
Other material by Sallust and ps‑Sallust are also available from the page.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete Latin texts, English translations
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Caesar/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric4" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Caesar/icon.jpg
			" ALT="
[image ALT: The stone head of a balding man in middle age. It is an antique portrait-bust of Julius Caesar in Corinth (Greece). On this site, it serves as the icon for Caesar's works.]
			"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="a0 start justify">
			<A CLASS="bold" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Caesar/Gallic_War/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
The <I>Gallic War</I>
			</A>
and
			<A CLASS="bold" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Caesar/Civil_Wars/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
The <I>Civil Wars</I>
			</A>
(military history by the man who made it: the Roman conquest of Gaul; then the defeat of Pompey as recounted by the victorious general, and the first step to the destruction of republican Rome; in each case, with maps of the principal battles).
			<P CLASS="i1 b0 justify">
And by others, but traditionally under Caesar's name:
			<A CLASS="bold" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Caesar/African_War/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
The <I>African War</I>
			</A>
•
			<A CLASS="bold" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Caesar/Alexandrian_War/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
The <I>Alexandrian War</I>
			</A>
•
			<A CLASS="bold" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Caesar/Spanish_War/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
The <I>Spanish War</I>
			</A>
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete English translations,
			<BR>
some of the Latin texts
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric4" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/icon.jpg
			" ALT="
[image ALT: A round metal plaque with an inscription. It is a phalera, a Roman military decoration. On this site, it serves as the icon for the works of Tacitus.]">
		</A></TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
			<B>
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Tacitus' <I>Histories</I> and <I>Annals</I>
			</A>
			</B>
are also notoriously well written; more importantly, they're also very well <I>thought</I>. My memory of Tacitus from my school days is of someone fiendishly hard to translate; in my old age, I'm glad that the interesting stories of the Year of the Four Emperors and the Batavian Revolt should be readable in English — and good English, too, by an excellent translator. (The <I>Annals</I> are less well translated, although not badly.)
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete English translation
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric2" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/icon.jpg
			" ALT="
[image ALT: A bust of a bald old man. It is a contemporary portrait of the emperor Vespasian, serving here as a link to the Lives of the Twelve Caesars by Suetonius.]">
		</A></TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
			<B>
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
The Lives of the Twelve Caesars by Suetonius
			</A>
			</B>
is the primary source for all kinds of information on the first twelve rulers of imperial Rome; some of it strange, some of it titillating, almost all of it just plain interesting. The surviving bits of
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
The Lives of Famous Men
			</A>
(Grammarians, Poets, Rhetoricians, and a few others) are also onsite.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete Latin text and English translation
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Historia_Augusta/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric2" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Historia_Augusta/icon.jpg
			" ALT="
[image ALT: A bust of a curly-haired man with a ferocious expression. It is a contemporary portrait of the emperor Caracalla, serving here as a link to the Historia Augusta.]">
		</A></TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
			<B>
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Historia_Augusta/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
The Historia Augusta
			</A>
			</B>
is also a primary source, sort of: picking up where Suetonius left off, but mixing in great gobs of fantasy, falsification and forgery; not so much a mine, as a minefield of information.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete Latin text and English translation
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Curtius/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric2" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Curtius/icon.jpg
			" ALT="
[image ALT: A small map of the empire of Alexander the Great, from Greece to India; superimposed on it, the representation of Alexander and his horse Bucephalus on the famous mosaic in Pompeii.]
			"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
			<B>
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Curtius/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Quintus Curtius:
			</A>
			</B>
The history of the conquests of Alexander the Great. If you are new to Latin, in addition to being an interesting, readable story — it's also a very easy text to read in the original. For this reason, excerpts of this work are often given as homework; therefore I have no intention of putting any translation of it online.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete Latin text with critical apparatus
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Isidore/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric4" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Isidore/icon.jpg
			" ALT="
[image ALT: Link to the text of Isidore of Seville]"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
			<B><A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Isidore/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Isidore of Seville: Etymologies.
			</A></B>
Last of the writers of Roman antiquity, first of the medieval world, the bishop of Hispalis left us both more and less than he lets on from the title of the work. Less, because as etymology goes, he shares with all Roman scholars (even Varro) a taste for the most facile, dubious or even fantastic word origins; far more, because sensing the end of a world, he preserved us an encyclopedic record of it. The Latin is so very easy, by the way — except for Book II — that almost all of the <I>Origines</I> can be read by any first-year Latin student: another text to cut your teeth on.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete Latin text
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Quintilian/Institutio_Oratoria/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric4" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Quintilian/icon.jpg
			" ALT="[Link to the text of Quintilian]"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
Quintilian's
			<B><A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Quintilian/Institutio_Oratoria/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Institutio Oratoria
			</A></B>
is his only work to have come down to us: a teacher's manual to the education of a young orator, it's essential reading for anyone who wants to understand Roman education, literature and style, trial procedure. Quintilian's warm personality and his sympathetic and commonsense approach to teaching (a good teacher is a wonderful resource) and many vignettes of Roman life make the book a surprisingly good read.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[ 2/22/04:</B>
complete English translation,
			<BR>
<!-- DATEDTEXT -->although not fully proofread
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Gellius/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric4" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Gellius/icon.jpg
			" ALT="[Link to the text of Gellius]"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
The
			<B><A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Gellius/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Noctes Atticae
			</A></B>
of Aulus Gellius are a large miscellany of antiquarian and philological notes. The text on LacusCurtius was rescued from another website that suddenly vanished — see my orientation page.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[ 10/12/06:</B>
complete Latin text
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Celsus/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric4" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Celsus/icon.jpg
			" ALT="[Link to the text of Celsus]"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
The
			<B><A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Celsus/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
De Medicina
			</A></B>
by A. Cornelius Celsus is properly only a rather small part of what ought to be the third encyclopedic work on this site, since in addition to medicine it included agriculture, military science, rhetoric, philosophy and jurisprudence; but only the section on medicine has survived.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[ 4/8/03:</B>
complete Latin text and English translation,
			<BR>
<!-- DATEDTEXT -->although not fully proofread
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cato/De_Agricultura/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric2" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Cato/icon.jpg
			" ALT="
[image ALT: The stone bust of a stern-looking old man, with curly hair but almost bald. It is a contemporary portrait of Cato the Elder.]
			"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
			<B><A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cato/De_Agricultura/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Cato's handbook on farming
			</A></B>
(the <I>de Re Rustica</I> or <I>de Agricultura</I>) is probably not all by him, and it's not very well put together, and it's been further disarranged over centuries of copying — and it's well worth reading if you want to get an idea not only of a Roman farm, but of the stuff the older Romans were made of.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete Latin text and English translation
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Varro/de_Re_Rustica/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric2" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Varro/de_Re_Rustica/icon.jpg
			" ALT="
[image ALT: A stylized drawing of a long rectangular building with a square tower at either end, in an even more stylized park. It is a 4c mosaic from the depicting an ancient Roman farm, and serves as the icon for Varro's 'de Re Rustica' on my site.]
			"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
			<B><A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Varro/de_Re_Rustica/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Varro's handbook on farming
			</A></B>
(the <I>de Re Rustica</I>) is a longer and more organized work, covering not only crops but livestock and the raising of poultry, game fowl, fish, bees, and dormice.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete Latin text and English translation
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Columella/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric2" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Columella/icon.jpg
			" ALT="
[image ALT: The stone bust of a stern-looking old man, with curly hair but almost bald. It is a contemporary portrait of Cato the Elder.]
