	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Oppian/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric4" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Oppian/icon.jpg
			" ALT="
[image ALT: A naïve drawing of a landscape, left to right: land and sea. On land, distant mountains but in the grassy foreground two dogs mating rear to rear; in the sea, a pair of sea monsters talking to each other, two eels twined around each other much like the snakes of a caduceus, a pair of fish; a lone eel advances from the sea to meet a snake at the shore. The scene illustrates a passage of Oppian's Cynegetica on the mating of various animals, and serves as my icon for that author.]
			"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
The complete extant output of
			<B><A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Oppian/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Oppian</A></B> is onsite: the <I>Cynegetica</I>, on Hunting; and the <I>Halieutica</I>, on Fishing; even more than hunting and fishing manuals, they are textbooks of zoology that mined the works of Aristotle and mediated him to the Middle Ages, when in turn they became one of the sources of all those wonderful bestiaries.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete Greek text and English translation
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric2" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Grattius/icon.jpg
			" ALT="
[image ALT: A photograph of the head of a hyena. It is my icon for the Cynegeticon, by Grattius.]
			"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
The
			<A CLASS="bold italic" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Cynegeticon
			</A>
of Grattius, a Roman author of the 1c <SPAN CLASS="small">A.D.</SPAN>, is another didactic poem on hunting. It runs to 500 lines, and is about weapons and nets and horses: but mostly about Dogs. Opinions differ as to just how good it might be.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete Latin text and English translation
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Nemesianus/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric2" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Nemesianus/icon.jpg
			" ALT="[Link to Nemesianus]"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
A third work on the hunt,
			<B><A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Nemesianus/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Nemesianus' <I>Cynegetica</I></A></B>, less technical and better versified — but he'd read Grattian. Unfortunately, not at all of it, probably not even most it, has survived. Four of the <I>Eclogues</I> now attributed to him are included also, as well as a fragment on <I>Bird-Catching</I>.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete Latin text and English translation
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
