	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Macrobius/Saturnalia/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric2" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Macrobius/Saturnalia/icon.jpg
			" ALT="
[image ALT: A piece of drawn-work, loosely speaking that's embroidery, depicting an old man in full stride and carrying a baby. The composition, surrounded by vine tendrils, also includes a scythe and a flaming pot on the ground: it can be taken as a representation of Saturn.]
			"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
			<B><A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Macrobius/Saturnalia/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Macrobius: <I>Saturnalia</I>.
			</A></B>
Although we only have parts of it, this book, written in the 5c <SPAN CLASS="small">A.D.</SPAN>, is one of the longest extant works from Late Antiquity; it purports, in the tradition of such works as Athenaeus' <I>Deipnosophistae</I>, to be a transcript of dinner table conversations over the December holidays in the house of Vettius Agorius Praetextatus (a major pagan literary and political figure of his time: see
			<A HREF="
E/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/Lazio/Roma/Rome/museums/Museo_Nazionale_Romano/Palazzo_Altemps/inscriptions/Vettius_Praetextatus.html
			"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
this page</A>), and is thus an informative if curious hodge-podge of antiquarian and philological lore, of medicine and literary criticism mostly of Vergil, in which many fragments of now lost ancient literature give us an idea of authors who would otherwise be mere names.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete Latin text
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Censorinus/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric2" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Censorinus/icon.jpg
			" ALT="
[image ALT: An astrological chart.]
			"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
			<B>
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Censorinus/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Censorinus: <I>de Die natali</I>.
			</A>
			</B>
An ancestor of the modern Festschrift, it was written in the 3c <SPAN CLASS="small">A.D.</SPAN> as a birthday gift for the author's beloved teacher. It is a clear-headed little book containing some fascinating information on music, astrology, and ancient philosophy and biology; it is particularly valuable today for its information on ancient chronology and the Roman calendar.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete Latin text and French translation
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/Strategemata/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric2" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/Strategemata/icon.jpg
			" ALT="
[image ALT: Link to the text of the Strategemata of Frontinus]"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
			<B><A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Frontinus/Strategemata/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
The <I>Strategemata</I> of Frontinus
			</A></B>
are a collection of over 500 examples of devices, ruses, ploys, creative ideas from history, intended by the Roman author as a sort of checklist for the military commander. The work is an appendix to his work on the Art of War, which has not survived; I suspect the interesting "stories" appealed far more to medieval copyists and readers than the deeper theoretical work: it's a great pity.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete Latin text and English translation
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Augustus/Res_Gestae/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric2" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Augustus/Res_Gestae/icon.jpg
			" ALT="[Link to the Res Gestae]"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
			<B><A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Augustus/Res_Gestae/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
The Monumentum Ancyranum
			</A></B>
(often called the <I>Res Gestae Divi Augusti</I>, which translates loosely as "The Achievements of the Emperor Augustus") is an unusual text in a couple of ways: it was written by an emperor, and it has come down to us not on parchment or paper, but chiseled on the stone walls of a building in Turkey. It is an exceptional first-hand source for the career of Augustus; presented here in 3‑column facing text, with critical apparatus and a wealth of notes for the mid-level student.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete bilingual Latin/Greek text and English translation
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Velleius_Paterculus/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric2" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Velleius_Paterculus/icon.jpg
			" ALT="[Link to the Velleius Paterculus homepage]"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
