	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Paulinus_Pellaeus/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric2" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Paulinus_Pellaeus/icon.jpg
			" ALT="[Link to Paulinus of Pella]"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
			<B><A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Paulinus_Pellaeus/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Paulinus of Pella
			</A></B>
was a very ordinary man who wound up living a somewhat extraordinary life because of the tenor of his times. He tells us that when he was in his twenties he liked pretty girls and fast cars, trendy fragrances and falconry — but he loses almost everything in the barbarian invasions and eventually gets religion. At 83 he summarizes his life for us: God has watched over him.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete Latin text and English translation
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric2" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Cicero/icon.jpg
			" ALT="[Link to Cicero]"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
There's also some
			<B><A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Cicero
			</A></B>
onsite; <!-- DATEDTEXT -->as of Nov 12, a bit less than 10% of his output: the <I>Cato de Senectute</I>, the <I>Laelius de Amicitia</I>, the <I>de Divinatione</I>, the <I>de Officiis</I>, and the <I>de Finibus</I>. I'm more interested in technical writing than in polemics or philosophy, so he's not high on my list; but more will probably follow.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
Latin texts, English translations
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ampelius/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric1" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Ampelius/icon.jpg
			" ALT="[Link to Ampelius]"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
			<B><A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ampelius/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Ampelius' <I>Liber Memorialis</I>
			</A></B>
is a summary of the essentials of world history, probably written in the 3c <SPAN CLASS="small">A.D.</SPAN>, for a little boy who "wanted to know everything". It gives us a view of history as younger Roman schoolboys were expected to learn it; it survived in a single manuscript, which in turn is now lost.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete Latin text
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Excerpta_Valesiana/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric2" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Excerpta_Valesiana/icon.jpg
			" ALT="[Link to the Excerpta Valesiana]"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
The
			<A CLASS="bold italic" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Excerpta_Valesiana/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Excerpta Valesiana
			</A>
(also known as the <SPAN CLASS="bold italic">Anonymus Valesianus</SPAN>) are in fact two different works written a century and a half apart. Both of them are short and surprisingly dull considering their interesting subjects: the first of them is a brief Life of Constantine; the other, written in some very nasty Latin, is a chronicle of the fall of the Roman empire and the reign of Theodoric.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete Latin text and English translation
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Agnellus/Liber_Pontificalis_Ecclesiae_Ravennatis/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric2" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Agnellus/Liber_Pontificalis_Ecclesiae_Ravennatis/icon.jpg
			" ALT="[Link to the Liber Pontificalis Ecclesiae Ravennatis]"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
The
			<A CLASS="bold italic" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Agnellus/Liber_Pontificalis_Ecclesiae_Ravennatis/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Liber Pontificalis Ecclesiae Ravennatis
			</A>
is a catalogue of some <SPAN CLASS="whole">forty-odd</SPAN> bishops of Ravenna. Written in the first half of the 9c in imitation of the much more important <I>Liber Pontificalis</I> (of the Bishops of Rome), it's a quirky document written in the most barbarous Latin, but with much to say about Ravenna, its church, and some background history of the late Roman Empire and the early Middle Ages.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete Latin text,
			<BR>
including the marginalia and Holder-Egger's notes
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>
</TABLE></DIV>


	<H3>
Greek Texts
	</H3>

<DIV ALIGN="center">
<TABLE CLASS="rubric whole">
	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric4" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/icon.jpg
			" ALT="[Link to the text of Herodotus]"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
			<B><A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Herodotus</A></B>, the Father of History (at least so far as Western civilization is concerned), can be found in many places online. Nevertheless, something more useful than a bare transcription seemed necessary, and Jona Lendering of Livius.Org and I set out to make it available: our text has been carefully annotated, embellished with over a hundred relevant original photographs, and provided with running links to Rawlinson's and How & Wells' commentaries.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete Greek text and English translation
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Polybius/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric4" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Polybius/icon.jpg
			" ALT="[Link to the text of Polybius]"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
			<B><A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Polybius/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
The <I>Histories</I> of Polybius</A></B>, a Greek writer, include large portions dealing with Greek history, as might be expected; but the author, a military man, was also a friend of Scipio's, and an eyewitness, at just the right time to leave us the most careful description of the Roman republican army, when it was conquering much of the Western world.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete English translation
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric4" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus/icon.jpg
			" ALT="
[image ALT: A stone cylinder, about 1 meter tall, carved with the heads of cattle decorated with fillets and garlands. It is a Roman altar in Bodrum (Turkey).]
			"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
			<A CLASS="bold" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
The <I>Roman Antiquities</I> of Dionysius of Halicarnassus
			</A>
is a somewhat idealized history of Rome, in which Augustus' empire is represented as the culmination of the Greek polis.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
complete English translation,
			<BR>
<!-- DATEDTEXT -->although not fully proofread
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric4" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/icon.jpg
			" ALT="
[image ALT: A small map of Sicily, with the Greek name of Diodorus superimposed on it.]
			"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
			<B>
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Diodorus Siculus' <I>Library of History</I>
			</A>
			</B>
is often said to be dull, but it's not: mostly just very long — and for some periods of Greek history, very valuable, as our only connected ancient account of them.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[4/11/12:</B>
Greek text — Books 6‑8;
			<BR>
English translation — Books 1‑32
			<B>]</B>
