Images/Roman/Texts/Aristotle/icon.jpg
			" ALT="[Link to Aristotle]"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
There's also a little dose of
			<B><A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Aristotle/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Aristotle
			</A></B>
— or ps‑Aristotle — onsite. <!-- DATEDTEXT -->As of Nov 12, just three items: <I>de Coloribus</I>, <I>de Mirabilibus Auscultationibus</I>, <I>Mechanica</I>. A bit more will probably follow, but again, don't expect much of the philosophical writings.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
			<B>[</B>
Greek texts, English translations
			<B>]</B>
		</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH="136"><P CLASS="start">
			<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Theophrastus/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
			<IMG TITLE="" CLASS="rubric1" SRC="
Images/Roman/Texts/Theophrastus/icon.jpg
			" ALT="
[image ALT: A photograph of a single bloom of Anemone sylvestris, serving as the icon on this site for the works of Theophrastus.]
			"></A>
		</TD>
		<TD>
			<P CLASS="start justify">
			<B><A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Theophrastus/home.html
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Theophrastus</A></B>, philosopher, polymath, and the Father of Botany, is <!-- DATEDTEXT -->for now represented onsite by two minor works of his, <I>Odors</I> and <I>Weather Signs</I>.
			<P CLASS="postsummary">
